page.title: 05ENVIRONMENT
page.content: TAWNY, BARN & SHORT-EARED OWLS, GREEN AND GREAT SPOTTED WOODPECKERS, RED & BLACK GROUSE, WOODCOCK AND GOLDCRESTS ARE ALL IN THE WOODS AND HILLS AROUND. NEARER TO THE VILLAGE A SURPRISING RANGE OF MAMMALS CAN BE SEEN: MULTITUDES OF RABBITS (DESPITE ENDEMIC MYXOMATOSIS) HARES, ROE DEER, RED SQUIRRELS, FERAL MINK (A NUISANCE TO FISH & WATER BIRDS) FOXES, STOATS, WEASELS, HEDGEHOGS AND BATS. WILD FLOWERS ABOUND, WILD ROSES FOLLOW THE COW PARSLEY & GREEN ALKANET ON THE ROADSIDES AND ALTHOUGH FORESTRY HAS OUSTED MANY BLUEBELLS AND PRIMROSES THEY ARE STILL FOUND ON WOODLAND RIDES. SMALL HEATH PLANTS SUCH AS MILKWORTS AND CINQUEFOIL ARE COMMON BUT ORCHIDS, BOG COTTON AND BOG ASPHODEL APPEAR ONLY WHERE HEATHER IS KEPT IN CONTROL. RIVERSIDES SUPPORT BUTTERBURS, KINGCUPS & MONKEY FLOWERS.
